# Note source data has "," as decimal separator.
AQ <- read.csv("AirQualityUCI.csv", sep=";", dec=",")
# X and X.1 have uncertain role and consist from only NAs
# let's filter it
AQ$X <- NULL
AQ$X.1 <- NULL

AQ_long <- gather(AQ, key="reagent", value="value", -c(Date,Time))
AQ_long$Date <- as.factor(AQ_long$Date)
AQ_long$Time <- as.factor(AQ_long$Time)
AQ_long$reagent <- as.factor(AQ_long$reagent)

# Robastic normalization (standartization)
rob_norm <- function(x) (x - median(x, na.rm = T)) / IQR(x, na.rm = T)

build_corr_analysis <- function(observations) {
  analysis <- list()
  # Cross-correlation workflow
  analysis$cor_matrix <- data.frame(abs(cor(observations,
                                            use = "complete.obs",
                                            method = "spearman")))
  analysis$cor_matrix$variables <- rownames(analysis$cor_matrix)
  #heatmap
  analysis$htmap <- gather(analysis$cor_matrix,
                           key = name, value = value, -variables) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(name, variables, fill = value)) + 
    geom_tile() + 
    scale_fill_gradient(low = "yellow", high = "red")
  
  # In heatmap red cells are low correlated and white and yellow high correlated
  # But, It's look like uncertain. Let`s try another way
  
  
  # Make principal component analisys
  PCA <- prcomp(na.omit(observations))
  
  # Look at variance per PCs
  
  analysis$pca_sdev <- data.frame(PC = 1:length(PCA$sdev), sdev = PCA$sdev) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = PC, y = sdev)) +
    geom_line() + geom_point()
  
  # Look at PCs histograms. 
  analysis$pcas_hist <- gather(data.frame(PCA$x)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
    geom_histogram() +
    facet_wrap(~key)
  
  
  # Ok. I don't fully understand, but it's matrix which consist of eigenvalues
  # which correspond to old variables.
  # And it's linear transformation above our data during evaluation new variables 
  # in PCA$x
  
  rotate <- data.frame(PCA$rotation)
  rotate$old_var <- rownames(PCA$rotation)
  
  analysis$percent <- round(100 * PCA$sdev^2 / sum(PCA$sdev^2), 2)
  
  # each point is a variable. and distances can be interpreted as correlation
  # between variables. If we think about it, we can see that almost all variables
  # (except PT08.S3.NOx) grouped pretty close each other.
  # Most likely it's relevant, because in practice wastes don't pollute enivorment
  # separately
  
  analysis$rotation <- ggplot(rotate, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2,
                                                color = old_var,
                                                label = old_var)) +
    geom_point(size = 0.1) + geom_text(size = 3) +
    xlab(paste("PC1", analysis$percent[[1]], "%")) +
    ylab(paste("PC2", analysis$percent[[2]], "%"))
    
    analysis$new_obj <- PCA
    
    analysis$kdeplot <- data.frame(PCA$x) %>% ggplot(aes(PC1, PC2)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.3, color = "black",size = 0.5) +
    geom_density2d(color = "red") + 
    xlab(paste("PC1", analysis$percent[[1]], "%")) +
    ylab(paste("PC2", analysis$percent[[2]], "%"))
    
  return(analysis)
  
}

PCA_recover <- function(PCA_data) {
  
  restore <- PCA_data$x %*% t(PCA_data$rotation)
  source_data <- t(t(restore) + PCA_data$center)
  return(data.frame(source_data))
  
}
